title: Repointed SXR -100um in X
FACET Plan for the weekend: beam to Faraday Cup at 2 nC
text: You read that correctly, 2 nC at operational phase with less than 100% laser power. Our goal for the weekend is to keep beam running to the Faraday cup (which only needs 10-2 on) and monitor the charge decay. If the charge starts to drop (or go up for that matter) leave it be, we want to see how it may change over a few days time. Please also note that 10-3 is off, and we will keep it that way. The station is producing some vacuum activity and we don't want to trip off the gun. TLDR keep the gun on with Faraday cup in. 10-3 stays off because it is producing vacuum activity again and will be processed up again next week.

title: Repointed (0,100) um for TMO
SXR Gain Length Meas. (pre-production)
text: If asked to measure the gain profile for TMO (they typically want to know how many unds till it saturates), can use the Gain Length GUI, still in preproduction. 1) Matlab 202a terminal 2) cd ~/aal/matlab/toolbox/GainLenghGUI 3) GainLengthGui_Backup 4) Settings: SXR Undulator, "Auto Run" mode to Move Undulators, Undulator Range 7 to 22, Average shots to 50 Begin with all the undulators in (confirm w/ TMO this is okay) and a red line or taper config saved you can restore to when done. Then push START. With above settings and 10 Hz, should take just a few minutes pulling unds one by one. When done, restore taper as you like. When finished, check Logbook box and press Logbook. You'll get a plot like the ones below. Labels are wrong (*cell number* is the one shown plus 13, and obviously is GMD and XGMD, not GDET). Looking for the point right where the rising line starts to curve over, indicating saturation, like the plots below. TMO may ask to remove all the ones after that.

Weekly BCS Checks -> strange behavior with IMBSY1B
text: While doing the weekly BCS checks, we noticed that the calibrate button did not work on IMBSY1B at first. When we first opened the rack, the calibration was set to 0.5, even though all 3 ACMs are usually set to 0.25. We set it to 0.25 and checked the high trip threshold by pressing the corresponding button, which moved the needle to 80 nA as expected. Then we pressed the calibrate button but the needle did not move at all. Then we moved the calibration setting back to 0.5 and tried pressing the calibrate button again, and this time the needle did move. Then we moved the calibration setting back to 0.25 again and pressed the calibrate button and the needle did move this time. We verified that it was tripping at 80 nA and moved on to the other ones. It is unclear why the calibrate button did not work at first, but it appears to be working fine now. Still, we should be mindful of this the next time we do BCS checks.

title: M. Gibbs has released updated code for photon energy calculation.
* Re: M. Gibbs has released updated code for photon energy calculation.
text: The calculation is done in the photonEnergyeV.m MATLAB script. Previously, undulators were considered "out" (and ignored for the energy calculation) if KAct < 0.1. When we extract the SXR undulator segments, the K only gets as low as 0.7, so they were never considered "out". I changed the threshold to KAct < 0.8, and it seems like the photon energy calculation is now properly ignoring the extracted segments. Now that the photon energy is calculated properly, the GMD should calculate the pulse intensity correctly even when segments are extracted. The threshold is the same for both HXR and SXR undulators. It looks like the new threshold will still be OK for both.
